00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:17.300
MALE SPEAKER: So
you described Lucy

00:49:17.300 --> 00:49:20.950
between around four to
three million years ago.

00:49:20.950 --> 00:49:24.180
Were there any other human
species or humanoid species

00:49:24.180 --> 00:49:25.950
at that time?

00:49:25.950 --> 00:49:27.449
In your diagram
there weren't any.

00:49:27.449 --> 00:49:28.990
DR. DONALD JOHANSON:
The question is,

00:49:28.990 --> 00:49:31.140
were there other
species of humans

00:49:31.140 --> 00:49:34.740
living at the same time as
Australopithecus, Afarensis,

00:49:34.740 --> 00:49:37.300
or Lucy's species.

00:49:37.300 --> 00:49:41.780
This is a question that we
are debating at the moment.

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:44.050
An Ethiopian colleague
of mine found

00:49:44.050 --> 00:49:46.800
at about 3.4
million years, which

00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:49.720
means a couple hundred
thousand years older than Lucy,

00:49:49.720 --> 00:49:53.645
north of where I work, a very
interesting foot skeleton

00:49:53.645 --> 00:49:57.990
and partial limb skeleton
that has a divergent toe.

00:49:57.990 --> 00:50:02.160
And that-- Lucy's
toe, or Afarensis,

00:50:02.160 --> 00:50:05.550
we have a complete articulated
foot that we found one year.

00:50:05.550 --> 00:50:07.700
And those feet
are like our feet.

00:50:07.700 --> 00:50:10.070
You saw the
footprints and so on.

00:50:10.070 --> 00:50:13.180
So he thinks that's
a new species.

00:50:13.180 --> 00:50:15.860
He hasn't named it a
new species right now,

00:50:15.860 --> 00:50:18.110
but I know in private
conversation with him

00:50:18.110 --> 00:50:20.220
that he is on the verge
of putting together

00:50:20.220 --> 00:50:22.780
an argument that it
is another species.

00:50:22.780 --> 00:50:24.915
That would probably
be a species that

00:50:24.915 --> 00:50:29.050
is a descendant of Ardipithecus,
which I haven't talked about,

00:50:29.050 --> 00:50:31.530
which is at 4.4 million.

00:50:31.530 --> 00:50:35.820
And while-- and it has a
very large divergent toe.

00:50:35.820 --> 00:50:37.950
So there may be
two lineages there.

00:50:37.950 --> 00:50:43.030
There is a discovery
by the Leakey family

00:50:43.030 --> 00:50:46.260
on the west side of Lake
Turkana, which they have

00:50:46.260 --> 00:50:48.570
given a new species name to.

00:50:48.570 --> 00:50:52.620
And most people don't think
it's probably a new species.

00:50:52.620 --> 00:50:54.450
But that may be another lineage.

00:50:54.450 --> 00:50:58.700
I think it would be very
unusual if Afarensis

00:50:58.700 --> 00:51:01.030
were the only species.

00:51:01.030 --> 00:51:06.720
Even up as recently as 50,000
years ago on planet Earth,

00:51:06.720 --> 00:51:08.430
we had Homo neanderthalensis.

00:51:08.430 --> 00:51:09.530
We had Homo sapiens.

00:51:09.530 --> 00:51:14.280
We had Homo erectus, very
late Homo erectus in Java.

00:51:14.280 --> 00:51:19.740
We had Homo floresiensis, these
peculiar little hobbit-like

00:51:19.740 --> 00:51:21.970
creatures that are found
out in the end of the Malay

00:51:21.970 --> 00:51:23.180
Archipelago.

00:51:23.180 --> 00:51:26.300
And perhaps these
denisovans that have been

00:51:26.300 --> 00:51:28.950
recognized in genetic analyses.

00:51:28.950 --> 00:51:31.700
So at just about
every point you had

00:51:31.700 --> 00:51:33.570
three or four or five species.

00:51:33.570 --> 00:51:37.970
But then there was a major
winnowing of those species.

00:51:37.970 --> 00:51:43.570
And that is directly correlated,
really, with our emergence.

00:51:43.570 --> 00:51:47.430
Wherever Homo sapiens went,
whatever species was there

00:51:47.430 --> 00:51:51.470
as a human species, very
rapidly disappeared.

00:51:51.470 --> 00:51:55.490
And there is an interesting
article by one of my colleagues

00:51:55.490 --> 00:51:58.110
at the Institute of Human
Origin, Curtis Marion,

00:51:58.110 --> 00:52:00.890
in the September issue, the
cover issue of the "Scientific

00:52:00.890 --> 00:52:02.890
American" in
September, called "How

00:52:02.890 --> 00:52:05.280
Humans Conquered the Planet."

00:52:05.280 --> 00:52:10.140
And in there he makes a
case that the refinement

00:52:10.140 --> 00:52:13.590
of the features that
we really consider

00:52:13.590 --> 00:52:17.700
as modern human, symbolic
language, cumulative culture,

00:52:17.700 --> 00:52:21.800
and significant cooperation,
division of labor, and so on,

00:52:21.800 --> 00:52:27.220
really emerged in Africa, in
that very diverse, mosaic set

00:52:27.220 --> 00:52:28.450
of environments.

00:52:28.450 --> 00:52:32.380
Neanderthals had evolved into
a separate species in Europe

00:52:32.380 --> 00:52:35.390
directly in response
to two things.

00:52:35.390 --> 00:52:37.500
One was genetic
isolation, so there

00:52:37.500 --> 00:52:41.410
was recombination, and
mutation, and natural selection.

00:52:41.410 --> 00:52:46.160
But also a physical,
physiological, and anatomical

00:52:46.160 --> 00:52:49.300
adaptations to a
periglacial environment.

00:52:49.300 --> 00:52:52.890
They were living with glaciers
in the distance, three, four

00:52:52.890 --> 00:52:54.390
miles thick.

00:52:54.390 --> 00:52:56.970
And their anatomy shows that.

00:52:56.970 --> 00:53:00.760
But he thinks that the things
that really make us who we are

00:53:00.760 --> 00:53:04.490
today came out of Africa,
which alters dramatically,

00:53:04.490 --> 00:53:07.380
and I've said this for
years, the early view we see

00:53:07.380 --> 00:53:11.110
in "Time-Life" books on
early man of this upright,

00:53:11.110 --> 00:53:17.240
white skin, French looking guy
in Europe, as the first humans.

00:53:17.240 --> 00:53:20.260
Whereas, I think it was probably
a much darker skinned people

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:23.510
who came out of Europe and
displaced Neanderthals.

00:53:23.510 --> 00:53:27.930
Brought about the extinction
of flores, floresiensis,

00:53:27.930 --> 00:53:30.320
erectus, and so on.

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:33.410
So I'd be very surprised
if there were not

00:53:33.410 --> 00:53:37.558
other lineages or other
species at the same time.

00:53:45.470 --> 00:53:48.530
MALE SPEAKER: If I am
remembering correctly,

00:53:48.530 --> 00:53:53.860
you said that Afarensis lived
to about three million years ago

00:53:53.860 --> 00:53:57.970
and the earliest Homo
species was 2.8 million.

00:53:57.970 --> 00:54:03.390
What is it that distinguishes
Homo from Australopithecus

00:54:03.390 --> 00:54:06.780
that you can say, now
we've got a new genus?

00:54:06.780 --> 00:54:10.410
DR. DONALD JOHANSON: Well,
I showed you the mandible.

00:54:10.410 --> 00:54:12.470
And there are a number
of features in there,

00:54:12.470 --> 00:54:14.760
the shape, the
elongation of the teeth,

00:54:14.760 --> 00:54:17.030
the reduction of
buttressing of the anterior

00:54:17.030 --> 00:54:20.610
portion of the mandible,
the particular place where

00:54:20.610 --> 00:54:23.840
the, what's called, the
ascending ramus arises,

00:54:23.840 --> 00:54:26.450
and the shape of the arch
in a parabolic fashion.

00:54:26.450 --> 00:54:29.200
We don't know exactly
why those came about.

00:54:29.200 --> 00:54:31.840
We think it had
something to do with more

00:54:31.840 --> 00:54:35.930
flexion of the cranial basal
areas of the skull that

00:54:35.930 --> 00:54:39.590
brought this face in
and shortened the arch.

00:54:39.590 --> 00:54:42.110
And in relation to that,
it began to broaden.

00:54:42.110 --> 00:54:44.320
But there are lots of
people working on that

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:45.660
trying to figure that out.

00:54:45.660 --> 00:54:47.990
It isn't just the stone tools
that are found with them,

00:54:47.990 --> 00:54:51.680
because that doesn't
define a species.

00:54:51.680 --> 00:54:53.820
And the upper jaw I
showed you, I think,

00:54:53.820 --> 00:54:58.840
was very convincingly different
from an Australopithecus.

00:54:58.840 --> 00:55:01.590
So what we would like
to see, of course,

00:55:01.590 --> 00:55:06.430
are cranial remains to see if
there's much difference in not

00:55:06.430 --> 00:55:08.160
only cranial
capacity, but cranial

00:55:08.160 --> 00:55:11.030
shape between Australopithecus.

00:55:11.030 --> 00:55:15.680
Now the palate, if we look
at it in lateral view,

00:55:15.680 --> 00:55:18.110
is not prognathic or projecting.

00:55:18.110 --> 00:55:19.700
It's very flat like ours.

00:55:19.700 --> 00:55:22.030
Our faces are very flat.

00:55:22.030 --> 00:55:24.200
So there are those
subtle features

00:55:24.200 --> 00:55:27.510
that all line up and
accumulate to convince us

00:55:27.510 --> 00:55:30.020
that that Homo is very
different from Australopithecus.

00:55:33.239 --> 00:55:34.530
Does that answer your question?

00:55:37.892 --> 00:55:38.850
MALE SPEAKER: One more.

00:55:41.740 --> 00:55:43.820
MALE SPEAKER: So you
mentioned that most

00:55:43.820 --> 00:55:49.590
of the fossils of Lucy's
species are kept in the National

00:55:49.590 --> 00:55:51.991
Museum in Ethiopia.

00:55:51.991 --> 00:55:53.740
DR. DONALD JOHANSON:
All of the specimens.

00:55:53.740 --> 00:55:56.800
All of the specimens that
have been found in Ethiopia

00:55:56.800 --> 00:55:59.950
of human ancestors now
reside in the National Museum

00:55:59.950 --> 00:56:01.680
in Addis Ababa, yes.

00:56:01.680 --> 00:56:04.590
MALE SPEAKER: So, given what's
happening, like in Syria

00:56:04.590 --> 00:56:08.550
and so on, are you worried that
someday somebody may steal them

00:56:08.550 --> 00:56:10.300
or-- or what are we
doing to protect them?

00:56:10.300 --> 00:56:12.091
DR. DONALD JOHANSON:
Well, I'm more worried

00:56:12.091 --> 00:56:14.030
that there's going to
be a massive earthquake.

00:56:14.030 --> 00:56:16.030
As you get earthquakes,
you know the Rift Valley

00:56:16.030 --> 00:56:19.450
is very unstable like
California and the Western coast

00:56:19.450 --> 00:56:21.530
and the Ring of Fire.

00:56:21.530 --> 00:56:27.090
They are stored in
very substantial safes.

00:56:27.090 --> 00:56:29.970
There are guards at the
museum all the time.

00:56:29.970 --> 00:56:34.760
There is a trained group
of Ethiopian scholars now,

00:56:34.760 --> 00:56:36.890
who are totally
dedicated to this.

00:56:36.890 --> 00:56:40.760
Some of them are in still
Ethiopia teaching or working

00:56:40.760 --> 00:56:43.490
full time at the ministry.

00:56:43.490 --> 00:56:45.990
But of course, we never know.

00:56:45.990 --> 00:56:50.260
I think there is no
anti-evolution movement

00:56:50.260 --> 00:56:54.090
in Ethiopia like there
has been in Kenya because

00:56:54.090 --> 00:56:58.380
of these radical Baptists
who have been going over

00:56:58.380 --> 00:57:00.820
there and converting
everybody to Christianity

00:57:00.820 --> 00:57:03.110
and saying that this evidence
needs to be destroyed,

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:06.820
sort of like the
ISIS point of view.

00:57:06.820 --> 00:57:09.717
It would be very difficult
for anyone to steal these.

00:57:09.717 --> 00:57:11.300
It would be very
difficult for anybody

00:57:11.300 --> 00:57:14.840
to come in and destroy them.

00:57:14.840 --> 00:57:16.280
But we never know what happens.

00:57:16.280 --> 00:57:20.610
In 1940-- when was Pearl Harbor?

00:57:20.610 --> 00:57:21.280
Was that '41?

00:57:25.180 --> 00:57:28.090
All the Homo erectus, all
the Peking Man fossils,

00:57:28.090 --> 00:57:33.120
were shipped from Peking to
the China Sea, South China Sea,

00:57:33.120 --> 00:57:36.300
to save them from the invasion.

00:57:36.300 --> 00:57:37.820
And they vanished.

00:57:37.820 --> 00:57:39.050
They've never been found.

00:57:39.050 --> 00:57:42.120
They never made it
aboard the USS Harrison.

00:57:42.120 --> 00:57:44.490
So things like that happen.

00:57:44.490 --> 00:57:48.090
Yet on the other hand, you
have the first Neanderthal

00:57:48.090 --> 00:57:54.860
found in 1856 in the
Neander Valley, Neanderthal,

00:57:54.860 --> 00:57:56.220
near Dusseldorf.

00:57:56.220 --> 00:58:00.570
And that survived and
still is in Dusseldorf,

00:58:00.570 --> 00:58:02.680
because it was kept in a safe.

00:58:02.680 --> 00:58:05.030
And was the first
fossil Neanderthal,

00:58:05.030 --> 00:58:08.030
the first fossil human
ever found in Europe.

00:58:08.030 --> 00:58:11.990
But in addition to that, it
was the first fossil specimen

00:58:11.990 --> 00:58:14.070
that gave us DNA.

00:58:14.070 --> 00:58:17.720
They drilled into the arm
bone of this 1856 Neanderthal,

00:58:17.720 --> 00:58:20.950
that nobody even knew
about genes back then.

00:58:20.950 --> 00:58:22.530
Fortunately preserved.

00:58:22.530 --> 00:58:24.840
Fortunately organic
material in it.

00:58:24.840 --> 00:58:27.930
And fortunately getting
a DNA sequence out of it.

00:58:27.930 --> 00:58:31.260
So it works both ways.

00:58:31.260 --> 00:58:35.660
But I firmly believe
that these fossils belong

00:58:35.660 --> 00:58:40.110
in the country of discovery,
and that it's incumbent on us

00:58:40.110 --> 00:58:44.110
as scholars, coming in
at their invitation,

00:58:44.110 --> 00:58:46.620
having this privileged
opportunity to come in,

00:58:46.620 --> 00:58:50.140
to help them establish
these organizations

00:58:50.140 --> 00:58:54.180
like a major laboratory,
like the National Museum,

00:58:54.180 --> 00:58:55.640
to house these specimens.

00:58:55.640 --> 00:58:57.860
And let's hope they do
continue to survive.

00:58:57.860 --> 00:59:00.490
Maybe someday someone
will develop a method

00:59:00.490 --> 00:59:03.490
to actually date the fossil
and not the volcanic ash,

00:59:03.490 --> 00:59:04.030
for example.

00:59:04.030 --> 00:59:07.574
That would be a
significant contribution.

00:59:07.574 --> 00:59:09.490
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you
very much for speaking

00:59:09.490 --> 00:59:10.073
with us today.

00:59:10.073 --> 00:59:12.280
We'll have time for a
book signing afterwards.

00:59:12.280 --> 00:59:14.230
So thank you for stopping by.

